    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips. i checked the soil and it seems pretty damp, so i don't think it's watering. could it be a nitrogen deficiency? how do i fix the soil ph to make sure they actually get the nutrients they need?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiency can indeed cause yellowing leaves, especially on the lower parts of the plant. To check for nitrogen deficiency, you can perform a simple soil test using a kit or send a sample to a lab. If it's a nitrogen deficiency, you can add a balanced fertilizer to the soil.\n\nAs for adjusting the soil pH, it's essential to note that tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH, between 6.0 and 7.0. You can use a soil test kit to determine your soil's pH level and adjust it accordingly. If your soil is too alkaline, you can add elemental sulfur or peat moss to lower the pH. However, if your soil is too acidic, you can add lime to raise the pH.\n\nIt's also worth considering that some nitrogen deficiencies can be caused by pH imbalances, so a balanced fertilizer and pH adjustment can help address the issue.",
